</table>
</solution>
</exercise>
</example>
<note id="fs-id1168345263165" class="try">
<exercise id="fs-id1168345417415">
<problem id="fs-id1168345445913">
<para id="fs-id1168341960985">Translate to a system of equations and solve:</para>
<para id="fs-id1168345743319">The ticket office at the zoo sold 553 tickets one day. The receipts totaled $3,936. How many $9 adult tickets and how many $6 child tickets were sold?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1168345425166">
<para id="fs-id1168345212275">There were 206 adult tickets sold and 347 children tickets sold.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</note>
<note id="fs-id1168345430694" class="try">
<exercise id="fs-id1168345420522">
<problem id="fs-id1168345285078">
<para id="fs-id1168345423397">Translate to a system of equations and solve:</para>
<para id="fs-id1168345420623">A science center sold 1,363 tickets on a busy weekend. The receipts totaled $12,146. How many $12 adult tickets and how many $7 child tickets were sold?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1168345259405">
<para id="fs-id1168345543588">There were 521 adult tickets sold and 842 children tickets sold.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</note>
<para id="fs-id1168345456866">In <link target-id="fs-id1168345255069"/> we’ll solve a coin problem. Now that we know how to work with systems of two variables, naming the variables in the ‘number’ column will be easy.</para>
<example id="fs-id1168345255069">
<exercise id="fs-id1168345416833">
<problem id="fs-id1168345425307">
<para id="fs-id1168345450081">Translate to a system of equations and solve:</para>
<para id="fs-id1168345374053">Priam has a collection of nickels and quarters, with a total value of $7.30. The number of nickels is six less than three times the number of quarters. How many nickels and how many quarters does he have?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1168345273505">
<title>Solution</title>
<table id="fs-id1167829590367" class="unnumbered unstyled can-break" summary="This figure says, “Step 1. Read the problem. We will create a table to organize the information. Step 2. Identify what we are looking for. We are looking for the number of nickels and the number of quarters. Step 3. Name what we are looking for. Let n = the number of nickels. Let q = the number of quarter. A table will help us organize the data. We have two types of coins, nickels and quarters. Write n and q for the number each type of coin. Fill in the value column with the value of each type of coin. The value of each nickel is $0.05. The value of each quarter is $0.25. The number times the value gives the total value, so the total value of the nickels is n times 0.05 = 0.05 times n and the total value of quarters is q times 0.25 = 0.25 times q. Altogether the total value of the coins is $7.30.” The table has four columns and three rows, except for the fourth column which has a fourth row. The columns are labeled, “Type” and “Number times Value = Total Value.” Under “Type” are “nickels” and “quarters.” Under “Number” are n and q. Under “Value” is 0.05 and 0.25. Under “Total Value” are 0.05 times n, 0.25 times q, and 7.30. The figure says, “Step 4. Translate into a system of equations. The total value column gives one equation. 0.05n + 0.25q = 7.30. We also know the number of nickels is six less than three times the number of quarters. Translate to get the second equation. N = 3q – 6. Now we have the system to solve.” The equations are 0.05n + 0.25q = 7.30 and n = 3q - 6. The figure says, “Step 5. Solve the system of equations. We will use the substitution method. Substitute n = 3q -6 into the first equation. Simplify and solve for q.” Thus the equation 0.05n + 0.25q = 7.30 becomes 0.05 times (3q – 6) + 0.25q = 7.3. This becomes 0.15q -0.3 + 0.25q = 7.3 or 0.4q – 0.3 = 7.3. Thus 0.4q = 7.6 or q = 19. The figure then says, “To find the number of nickels, substitute q = 19 into the second equation. Thus, n = 3q – 6 becomes n = 3 times 19 – 6 or n = 51. The figure says, “Check the answer in the problem.” 19 quarter at $0.25 = $4.75 and 51 nickels at $0.05 = $2.25. $4.75 plus $2.25 = $7.30. 3 times 19 – 6 = 51. The figure then says, “Step 7. Answer the question. Priam has 19 quarters and 51 nickels.”">
