<section id="fs-id1168345210850">
<title>Solve Interest Applications</title>
<para id="fs-id1168345386146">The formula to model interest applications is <emphasis effect="italics">I</emphasis> = <emphasis effect="italics">Prt</emphasis>. Interest, <emphasis effect="italics">I</emphasis>, is the product of the principal, <emphasis effect="italics">P</emphasis>, the rate, <emphasis effect="italics">r</emphasis>, and the time, <emphasis effect="italics">t</emphasis>. In our work here, we will calculate the interest earned in one year, so <emphasis effect="italics">t</emphasis> will be 1.</para>
<para id="fs-id1168345449160">We modify the column titles in the mixture table to show the formula for interest, as you’ll see in <link target-id="fs-id1168345286291"/>.</para>
<example id="fs-id1168345286291">
<exercise id="fs-id1168345449931">
<problem id="fs-id1168345230935">
<para id="fs-id1168345301687">Translate to a system of equations and solve:</para>
<para id="fs-id1168345254082">Adnan has $40,000 to invest and hopes to earn 7.1% interest per year. He will put some of the money into a stock fund that earns 8% per year and the rest into bonds that earns 3% per year. How much money should he put into each fund?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1168345374070">
<title>Solution</title>
<table id="fs-id1167836554518" class="unnumbered unstyled can-break" summary="This figure says, “Step 1. Read the problem. A chart will help us organize the information. Step 2. Identify what we are looking for. We are looking for the amount to invest in each fund. Step 3. Name what we are looking for. Let s = the amount invest in stocks and b = the amount invested in bonds. Write the interest rate as a decimal for each fund. Multiply: Principal times Rate times Time to get the interest.” The table has five columns and four rows. The first row labels each column “Account” and “Principal times Rate times Time = Interest.” Under “Account” is stock fund, bonds, and total. Under “Principal” are s, b, and 40,000. Under “Rate” are 0.08, 0.03, 0.071. Under “Time” are 1 and 1 and nothing. Under “Interest” are 0.08s, 0.03b, and 0.071 times 40,000. The figure says, “Step 4. Translate into a system of equations. We get our system of equations from the Principal column and the Interest column.” The equations are s + b = 40,000 and 0.08x + 0.03b = 0.071 times 40,000. The figure says, “Step 5. Solve the system of equations. Solve by elimination. Multiply the top equation by -0.03. Simplify and add to solve for s.” Thus the equations become -0.03 times (s + b) = -0.03 times 40,000 and 0.08s + 0.03b = 2,840 or -0.03s – 0.03b = -1,200 and 0.08s - 0.03b = 2,840. These equations yield 0.05s = 1,640 or s = 32.800. The figure says, “To find b, substitute s = 32,800 into the first equation.” Thus s + b = 40,000 becomes 32,800 + b = 40,000 or b = 7,200. The figure says, “Step 6. Check the answer in the problem. We leave the check to you. Step 7. Answer the question. Adnan should invest &gt;2,000 in stock and $7,200 in bonds.”"><label/>
<tgroup cols="2"><tbody>
  <row>
    <entry valign="top"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 1. Read</emphasis> the problem.</entry>
    <entry valign="top">A chart will help us organize the information.</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
    <entry valign="top"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 2. Identify</emphasis> what we are looking for.</entry>
    <entry valign="top">We are looking for the amount to invest in each fund.</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
